Q!:
John Snow did not rely only on the evidence from the map. 
Instead, he collected a lot of data until he became sure that the pump and the contaminated water were the real cause of the problem.
Some of the most important things he did were:
1. He mapped the locations of the deaths and noticed that most of the cases were near the water pump.
2. He looked at the people who lived in the same area and close to the pump but did not get sick. 
He also studied people who became ill even though they lived far from the pump, such as the elderly woman whose helper used to bring her water from that same pump at different times.

